#let lesson = (
title: [Scenario Based Stalling]

,aim: [
Identify and recover from stalls in all configurations, attitudes, and power settings, with particular emphasis on realistic circuit and departure scenarios where inadvertent stalls are most likely.
]

,overview: [
Lesson 8 pairs with E7 (Slow Flight and Stall Recognition, Lesson 6) to satisfy the two-flight requirement for stalling competency. Where Lesson 6 focused on recognising and recovering from the approaching stall in straightforward configurations, this lesson places stalling in realistic flight scenarios — the go-around, turning flight, and engine failure after takeoff. The student must connect the aerodynamic knowledge from E7 and E9 to the actual high-risk scenarios they will encounter in circuits and early solo flight.

The elevator trim stall is introduced here as an important Phase 1 safety item. Spin entry awareness is discussed and demonstrated as a visual familiarisation exercise; intentional spinning is not conducted within this syllabus, and pro-spin inputs below manoeuvring speed are not permitted.

The instructor demonstrates all new scenario content; the student then practises each scenario under supervision. Full C standard for E10 requires the element to be revisited in Phase 3. The standard required here is S — sufficient for safe operations before first solo.
]

,learning_outcomes: [
#text(size:12pt)[*Knowledge*]
- Explain the aerodynamic conditions that produce an accelerated stall: G-loading, as occurs when a turn is tightened at approach speed
- Describe the stall in a turn: one wing stalls before the other; wing drop; aileron input worsens the situation — reinforce from E7
- Explain stall entry from a simulated go-around: full flap, low airspeed, rapid power increase, nose pitches up; if elevator follows, AoA exceeds critical
- Explain stall entry from EFATO scenario: excess rearward stick applied by the pilot; failure to lower the nose to glide attitude
- Describe the elevator trim stall: full nose-up trim at slow speed, sudden large power application; recognition; recovery sequence
- Describe the conditions required for spin entry and the importance of coordinated flight at high AoA

#text(size:12pt)[*Skills*]
- Complete the HASSELL check before the stalling sequence, and every 15 minutes
- Demonstrate stall recognition and recovery in a banked turn (turning stall) — relax backpressure; rudder to stop roll; ailerons neutral
- Demonstrate prevention of stall entry in a simulated go-around scenario
- Demonstrate recovery from a simulated EFATO stall scenario
- Recognise and recover from an elevator trim stall
- Apply correct recovery for any wing drop stall: relax backpressure; rudder to stop roll; ailerons neutral until unstalled

#text(size:12pt)[*Non-Technical Skills*]
- [SA] HASSELL before the sequence and every 15 minutes; 360° lookout scan before each stall entry
- [TEM] Identify the TEM chain that leads to each scenario stall: distraction in the go-around; fixation on landing area during EFATO; tightening the turn on base-to-final; brief countermeasures before flight
- [HF] Manage startle response in unexpected stall entries — reinforce from Lesson 6; the natural reflex (pull back) is the wrong response; brief before flight
- [CRM] Instructor confirms control handover procedure for this lesson; if the student is about to enter a spin, instructor takes control immediately
]

,theory_knowledge: [
- Aerodynamics — stalling in all configurations *(Pg 168–169)*
- Aerodynamics — accelerated stall in turns *(Pg 173)*
- Aerodynamics — spin entry, development, and recovery awareness *(Pg 170–171)*
- Human Factors — undesired aircraft states, TEM chain *(Pg 44–45, 48)*
- Human Factors — false hypothesis, confirmation bias *(Pg 35)*
- Human Factors — startle response countermeasures *(Pg 51)*
]

,ground_brief_topics: [
Total time: 35 minutes \
Equipment required: Aircraft model, whiteboard \

*Non-Technical Skills* (5 minutes)
- [TEM] The TEM chain that produces scenario stalls: tightening the turn on base-to-final; fixation on the landing area during EFATO; rushing the go-around; brief countermeasures for each
- [SA] HASSELL is mandatory before the stalling sequence begins and every 15 minutes; 360° lookout required
- [HF] Startle response — reinforce from Lesson 6; the body will pull back in response to an unexpected stall; this reflex must be overridden every time

*Accelerated Stall in a Turn* (5 minutes)
- Stall can occur at any speed if AoA is exceeded
- At 45° AoB the stall speed is 19% higher than wings-level — at approach speed, a base-to-final turn can easily exceed the stalling AoA if backpressure is applied
- Entry symptoms: faster onset than in straight flight; buffet arrives quickly; wing drop may be sudden
- Recovery: relax backpressure first; apply power; stop roll with rudder; ailerons neutral until unstalled

*Scenario 1 — Stall in a Turn (Base-to-Final)* (5 minutes)
- Context: overshooting the centreline; tightening the turn on base-to-final; adding backpressure in a 30–45° banked turn
- The inner wing stalls first (highest AoA); wing drops toward the inside; instinct to apply aileron worsens the situation
- Recovery: relax backpressure; rudder to stop roll; ailerons neutral until wing is unstalled
- Below 500 ft AGL: no recovery is possible — this scenario kills people; prevention is the only acceptable outcome

*Scenario 2 — Go-Around Stall* (5 minutes)
- Context: full power applied from approach configuration; pitch raised rapidly to arrest descent; airspeed still at approach speed
- With full flap and full power, the pitching moment pitches the nose steeply; if elevator follows, AoA rapidly exceeds critical
- Prevention: set go-around attitude and wait; do not chase airspeed; do not retract flap until a positive rate of climb is established
- Recovery before stall: level pitch to go-around attitude; allow airspeed to build; resume the go-around sequence

*Scenario 3 — EFATO Stall* (5 minutes)
- Context: engine fails on upwind; pilot applies excess backpressure, fails to lower the nose, or fixates on finding a landing area before establishing glide attitude
- Best glide attitude first — without exception; coordination maintained; accept the descent; no heroic altitude manoeuvres
- Reinforcement from Lesson 4 (Descending): the EFATO brief exists for this reason

*Elevator Trim Stall* (5 minutes)
- Context: aircraft trimmed heavily nose-up for slow flight or an approach; pilot applies full power and momentarily releases positive control (as in a rushed go-around)
- The trim force pitches the nose sharply upward; AoA rapidly exceeds critical; accelerated stall develops before the pilot re-applies control pressure
- Recognition: rapid uncommanded pitch-up immediately after power application; very short warning period
- Recovery: push forward against the trim force to reduce AoA; reduce power momentarily if pitch-up is extreme; re-establish go-around attitude; retrim
- Prevention: never apply full power without maintaining positive forward control pressure; hands on controls before throttle

*Spin Entry Awareness* (5 minutes)
- A spin requires: stall + yaw at the moment of stall
- Uncoordinated flight (ball displaced) at high AoA is the risk combination — this is why coordinated flight matters
- Visual cue of spin entry: rapid yaw/roll in one direction; nose pitches steeply down; rolling into the spin
- Recovery awareness: close throttle; opposite rudder; forward stick; recover from the dive (refer POH)
- Emphasis: awareness only; intentional spinning is not part of this training; pro-spin inputs below Va are not permitted
]

,ground_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor*]
- Review weather, NOTAMs, and maintenance release with student — smooth air essential; ceiling >3500 ft AGL required; postpone if turbulent
- Brief HASSELL minimum height for today; confirm with student before takeoff
- Brief elevator trim stall recovery sequence on the ground; confirm student recall before flight

#text(size:12pt)[*Student*]
- Complete IMSAFE self-assessment and operations whiteboard
- Lead pre-flight inspection independently; complete documentation
- Obtain NAIPS TAF; check BOM radar; brief conditions and suitability to instructor
- Conduct start, taxi, runup, and all checklists to takeoff independently
- Deliver pre-takeoff safety brief before taxi independently
]

,in_flight_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*E8 Takeoff — Lesson 8*]
Student conducts the takeoff independently. Instructor does not prompt during ground roll or lift-off unless a safety issue arises. After-takeoff checks without prompting.

#text(size:12pt)[*Demonstration*]
HASSELL check completed by student before the manoeuvre sequence. Instructor demonstrates each scenario with full patter; student follows through on controls.

- *Coordinated turning stall at 30° AoB*: Entry; wing drop; correct recovery — relax backpressure, rudder to stop roll, ailerons neutral; patter the pro-recovery sequence
- *Slipping turn stall at 30° AoB*: Entry; wing drop; correct recovery — note how the slip increases the outer wing's AoA; patter the difference from the coordinated stall
- *Go-around scenario*: Simulated approach configuration; go-around initiated; aggressive pitch-up demonstrated to show the stall entry point; recovery before stall develops; patter prevention
- *EFATO scenario*: Vy climb; power to idle; demonstrate partial nose-lowering then fixation; patter stalling control position, symptoms, and recovery
- *Elevator trim stall*: Set full nose-up trim at slow speed; apply full power; demonstrate the pitch-up onset; recovery — push forward against trim force; patter the recognition and sequence
- *Spin entry awareness*: Demonstrate entry conditions above Va only; patter visual cues and control positions; recover immediately; brief before entry

#text(size:12pt)[*Student Practice*]
- *HASSELL check*: Student completes before sequence; every 15 minutes thereafter
- *Straight and level stalls — review*: Clean and approach configurations; one of each; confirm Lesson 6 standard is retained
- *Turning stall at 30° AoB*: Student enters; wing drop; relax backpressure; rudder to stop roll; ailerons neutral; recover to Vy climb; height loss ≤400 ft
- *Go-around scenario*: Student simulates approach; executes go-around; instructor prompts "nose up" at an unexpected moment; student prevents stall entry by holding go-around attitude
- *EFATO scenario*: Instructor simulates engine failure on upwind; student lowers nose to glide attitude; maintains coordination; does not apply excess backpressure
- *Elevator trim stall*: Student sets full nose-up trim at slow speed; instructor calls "go-around"; student applies full power while maintaining positive forward control; recognises the pitch-up tendency; recovers correctly
]

,common_errors:[
- *Aileron on wing drop in turning stall*: Relax backpressure first; rudder to stop roll; aileron neutral until unstalled — reinforce from Lesson 6 every time.
- *Aggressive pitch in go-around*: Power + attitude = performance; set the go-around attitude and wait; do not chase airspeed.
- *Excess backpressure in EFATO glide*: Use the positive stability of the aircraft; accept the descent; the nose will settle to an appropriate glide attitude if released.
- *Trim stall — releasing controls on power application*: Hands on controls before throttle is advanced; positive forward pressure maintained throughout the power application.
- *HASSELL omitted*: Non-negotiable; NC for the whole sequence.
]

,post_flight:[
- *Student Self-Assessment* (5 min): Student reviews each scenario; identifies the TEM chain for each; self-assesses recovery technique and height loss.
- *Instructor Feedback* (5 min):
  - Evaluate against completion standards (P, S, or NC) per scenario.
  - Reinforce the connection between each scenario and its real-world context.
  - Note: with this lesson complete and Lesson 6 previously recorded, the two-flight stalling requirement is now satisfied.
- *Theory Check* (5 min): Student explains why aileron worsens a wing drop and what conditions are required for spin entry.
- *Next Steps*: Assign homework. Preview Lesson 9 (Phase 1 Consolidation): all Phase 1 elements assessed in a connected flight.
]

,standards_for_progression:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Progressing (P) — may advance to Lesson 9*]
- *Turning stall*: Rudder applied on wing drop with one prompt; ailerons neutral; height loss ≤400 ft
- *Go-around stall prevention*: Identifies stall risk and prevents entry with instructor guidance
- *EFATO scenario*: Maintains coordination and glide attitude with minor prompting
- *Elevator trim stall*: Recognises pitch-up tendency; recovery initiated with minor prompting
- *HASSELL*: Completed before sequence with occasional reminder

#text(size:12pt)[*Solo Standard (S) — required before first solo and for Phase 3 entry*]
- *Turning stall*: Relax backpressure; rudder promptly on wing drop without prompting; ailerons neutral; recovery smooth; height loss ≤300 ft
- *Go-around stall prevention*: Consistently prevents stall entry; controlled pitch attitude; no instructor intervention
- *EFATO scenario*: Correct glide attitude achieved; coordinated; no excess backpressure; no prompting
- *Elevator trim stall*: Recognises pitch-up; pushes forward against trim force; recovers correctly without prompting
- *HASSELL*: Completed before sequence and every 15 minutes without prompting
- *Note*: Full C standard requires the element to be revisited in Phase 3. Two-flight stalling requirement (E7 + E10) is now satisfied.

- *Outcome*: Recorded in student training record as P, S, or NC with specific comments.
]

,safety:[
- *Weather*: Horizon clearly visible; ceiling >3500 ft AGL; smooth air essential — postpone if turbulent; wind <25 knots
- *Altitude*: All stall exercises above 2500 ft AGL; all recoveries complete by 2500 ft AGL; HASSELL minimum height enforced
- *Emergency Procedures*: Forced landing area preselected before HASSELL; instructor ready to intervene immediately if spin entry is imminent or minimum height is threatened
- *TEM*:
  - Brief elevator trim stall recovery and spin awareness on the ground; confirm student recall before flight
  - Spin entry awareness: brief precise conditions and immediate recovery sequence before flight; pro-spin inputs below Va are not permitted under any circumstances
  - Instructor takes control at first sign of incipient spin development — no delay
  - Go-around and EFATO scenarios: do not allow the aircraft to reach the stalling control position in these scenarios; these are prevention exercises, not recovery exercises
  - Monitor student for overload; pause between exercises; do not stack scenarios without recovery time
]

,homework:[
- Read Bob Tait's RAAus Study Guide:
  - Aerodynamics: Pg 168–173 (stalling in all configurations, accelerated stall, spin entry)
  - Human Factors: Pg 35, 44–45, 48, 51 (false hypothesis, undesired aircraft states, countermeasures)
- Prepare for Lesson 9 (Phase 1 Consolidation and Radio Essentials):
  - VHF Radio: Pg 55–58 (CTAF procedures, call structure)
  - Air Legislation: Pg 256 (airspace classifications)
  - Human Factors: Pg 45 (communication errors)
- Reflect:
  - "Name three circuit scenarios where an inadvertent stall is most likely. For each: what is the TEM chain? What is the prevention?"
  - "What is the difference between a stall with a wing drop and a spin? What does this mean for your recovery technique?"
  - "Why is an elevator trim stall particularly dangerous during a rushed go-around?"
]
)

